Update and refactor code to improve code quality
commitResults.messageBody:
Code does not follow code quality standards.
It also has coding standard violations.

Updating and refactoring the code allows the code to be more readable,
and follows the standard that was provided.

Let's,
- update the boolean names
- have a static method to handle initializing of tasks objects for
  event, deadline and todo tasks
- shift some parts of addTask function to command function

This is done as:
- better boolean names will fit the coding standard (use of "is")
- task constructors does not have an obvious happy path and it makes
  better sense for the parsing to be done in another function, and for
  the constructor to only handle assignments of variables
- the else block in the command should be used to catch error instead
  of leaving command errors to be handled by the add function [code
  quality violation]

commitResults.messageTitle: Add assertions to Parser and SaveSystem classes
Add assertions to Task child classes
commitResults.messageBody:
There are no assertions to define assumptions about the input
parameters for the Task child public constructor

Any classes can call the constructors as they are public, but the
constructors had assumed that they are called for the right purpose.
Wrong calls would fail for the wrong errors.

Add assertions to the constructors to check if the assumptions hold.

It is better to have assertions because it will ensure the functions
input parameters follows the assumption.

Add update task functionality
commitResults.messageBody:
No way to update a task detail unless user deletes and adds it again.

This causes inconvenience to the user. Also, since we can update
mark within the system, detail should also be allowed to update within
the system.

Let's,
- add an update command that allows user to select a specific task to
  modify the details.
- add an updateTask function to TaskList to get the specific task
- add an updateDetails function to each of the Task child classes to
  handle update for each of their own type of details field.

Splitting the implementation this way is to maintain the abstraction
and encapsulation properties of OOP programming for the classes.
